{"ts":"2026-06-27T17:28:49.918Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing the Rich Data**\n\nI'm struck by the richness of `ApiDocumentItem` with properties like `id`, `title`, and `version`. My primary focus now is integrating this information into the layout effectively. The goal is to determine the best visual presentation. I'm actively assessing various layout strategies.\n\n\n**Revising Layout Strategies**\n\nI'm now iterating on the lower strip and the bento grid for the layout. Initially, I'm considering a three-column approach for the lower strip, with dedicated sections for the Financial Ledger, Cryptographic Vault (displaying recent documents), and Internal Operations Shell. Alternatively, I am testing the bento grid for the top row, and considering different bento configurations. I'm exploring options to integrate documents seamlessly, perhaps within a combined Clients, Projects, & Documents overview, or dedicating a bento card specifically to Cryptographic Credentials and Documents.\n\n\n**Optimizing Bento Arrangements**\n\nI'm now refining the bento grid's arrangement, considering a four-column structure that adapts responsively. I've laid out an initial arrangement: Clients & Projects, AI Model Operations, SLA Wires & Governance Alerts, and Sovereign Documents Vault. I'm verifying the container classes to ensure proper column spanning and responsiveness across devices. Now, I'm thinking of placing documents in the lower tier next to the Financial Ledger!\n\n\n**Visualizing Column Layouts**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on a three-column layout for the lower strip, with an elegant, responsive approach! My revised approach ensures that the **Financial Ledger** and **Sovereign Document Vault** each have individual columns, followed by the **Internal Operations Shell**. This should offer a clear presentation.\n\n\n**Verifying Final Layout**\n\nI've finalized the lower strip layout! The Internal Operations Shell now spans two columns on larger screens (using `lg:col-span-2`), housing the command log console and interactive triggers. I've re-confirmed the `grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-4` structure, with individual columns for the Financial Ledger and Sovereign Document Vault. This balances screen use and fulfills all requirements. I'm also confirming the four key KPIs at the top: Sandboxes/Clusters, AI Node Loops, SLA Active Wires, and Governance/ISO Status, based on backend summary data.\n\n\n**Defining Dynamic States**\n\nI'm now defining the states needed for the dashboard display! I've determined that the `loading` state requires a premium, terminal-style skeleton with spinning nodes. When the data is `empty`, I must display a concise message \"NO SOVEREIGN RECORDS RESOLVED\". I'll show an error box with a reconnect button for the `error` state. I'll also add a refresh button to re-fetch the dashboard data.\n\n\n**Mapping Interactive States**\n\nI'm now mapping out interactive states for new buttons! The CLI console logs confirm user actions: \"Purge Cache\" purges enclaves, \"Align Weights\" re-aligns boundaries, \"Probe\" initiates a kernel scan, and \"Lockdown\" isolates namespaces. The \"Ack\" button dynamically updates the support ticket state, which I can also log: `Ack support wire: ${t.id}`. This is promising!\n\n\n**Implementing Interactive States**\n\nI'm now implementing interactive states for the \"Ack\" and \"Verify\" buttons! I've set up local states to track acknowledgements and verifications. When a support ticket is acknowledged, the UI will change and a log will confirm this. Similarly, clicking \"Verify\" on governance alerts changes the UI and logs the remediation. This is exciting!\n\nI'm focused on the UI styling now. The current Phase 4 look and feel, with monospace text, custom borders, and dark backgrounds, exudes a high-end, administrative feel. We must preserve this quality.\n\n\n**Revisiting Original Design**\n\nI'm now re-examining the original design in `app/admin/dashboard/page.tsx` to prevent oversights. I'm focusing on lines 15-35, and I am especially noting the monospace font and the structured layout of the KPIs. The key here is to maintain consistency with the existing style, including the prominent use of terminal-style aesthetics. The use of custom borders and dark backgrounds should be preserved.\n\n\n**Confirming Necessary Icons**\n\nI'm now assessing potential icons for document representation within the dashboard. After reviewing `lucide-react`, I'm leaning toward `FileText`, `FileSpreadsheet`, or `ShieldCheck` for document-related indicators. I'm making sure these symbols align with the overall terminal style. The existing imports within `app/admin/dashboard/page.tsx` will be integrated, alongside `PrivatePageHeader`, to ensure layout integrity.\n\n\n**Selecting Lucide Icons**\n\nI'm now selecting appropriate Lucide icons for dashboard use. I'm focusing on icons such as `Server`, `Activity`, `Clock`, `ShieldCheck`, `CornerDownRight`, `FileText`, `Lock`, `AlertCircle`, `RefreshCw`, `Sliders`, `Database`, and `AlertTriangle`. These should work perfectly.\n\nI'm now designing a high-quality loading screen for the dashboard:\n\n```typescript\n  if (loading) {\n    return (\n      <div className=\"space-y-6 font-mono text-[11px] text-white animate-pulse\">\n        <PrivatePageHeader title=\"OVERSIGHT DECK\" desc=\"Establishing secure handshake with core mesh network...\" />\n        \n        {/* KPI skeleton */}\n        <div className=\"grid grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-4\">\n          {[1, 2, 3, 4].map((i) => (\n            <div key={i} className=\"p-4 rounded-xl border border-white/5 bg-[#050505]/20 flex justify-between items-center h-[65px]\">\n              <div className=\"space-y-2\">\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-16 bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n                <div className=\"h-4 w-24 bg-white/20 rounded\" />\n              </div>\n              <div className=\"w-4 h-4 rounded\" />\n            </div>\n          ))}\n        </div>\n        \n        {/* Lower strip skeleton */}\n        <div className=\"grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4\">\n          {[1, 2, 3].map((i) => (\n            <div key={i} className=\"p-4 rounded-xl border border-white/5 bg-[#050505]/20 h-[250px]\">\n              <div className=\"h-4 w-full bg-white/10 rounded mb-4\" />\n              <div className=\"space-y-2\">\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-1/2 bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-3/4 bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-1/4 bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-full bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-3/4 bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n                <div className=\"h-2 w-1/2 bg-white/10 rounded\" />\n              </div>\n            </div>\n          ))}\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    );\n  }\n```\n\n\n**Designing Error and Loading States**\n\nI'm now designing error and loading states, enhancing dashboard resilience! I've crafted a terminal-style loading state with spinning nodes and a skeleton UI. For the error state, there's a red-themed error box featuring `AlertCircle` and a reconnect button. I also made sure to add in a concise message for the `empty` state, using \"NO SOVEREIGN RECORDS RESOLVED\". The error state should make the user click the reconnect button.\n\n\n**Implementing Automatic Retry**\n\nI'm now implementing the automatic retry logic for the error state, making the user experience smoother. I've integrated a retry block that attempts to re-fetch the data automatically, alongside the existing \"Reconnect Enclave\" button, creating a fully custom error view. I'm also ensuring the empty state displays a clear, concise message: \"NO SOVEREIGN RECORDS RESOLVED\".\n\n\n\n**Integrating Dashboard Data**\n\nI'm now integrating the dashboard data! I've started on an empty state design, featuring a central displ